{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.42,0.26,0.11,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65267"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3079"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4641"},{"type":"tags","id":"4707"},{"type":"tags","id":"4821"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44432"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65267"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his syphilis treatment. He was diagnosed with tertiary syphilis three months ago after presenting with cognitive decline and personality changes. At that time, his Rapid Plasma Reagin (RPR) titre was 1:32, and he completed a course of intramuscular benzathine penicillin. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following serological results would determine an adequate response to treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["RPR titre 1:32 at 3 months","RPR titre 1:16 at 6 months","RPR titre 1:8 at 18 months","RPR titre 1:24 at 1 month","RPR titre 1:12 at 12 months"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment for syphilis, serological monitoring with RPR is essential to confirm adequate response. A fourfold (two dilution) decrease in titre within 12-24 months indicates appropriate response to therapy, with the initial titre in this case being 1:32.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERPR titre 1:8\u003C/strong\u003E at 18 months represents a fourfold decrease from the initial 1:32, which meets criteria for adequate treatment response. This is particularly appropriate in late syphilis where serological response may take up to 24 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERPR titre 1:32\u003C/strong\u003E at 3 months shows no change from baseline, suggesting possible treatment failure. This would warrant investigation for immunosuppression (particularly HIV infection) and consideration of retreatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERPR titre 1:16\u003C/strong\u003E at 6 months represents only a twofold (single dilution) decrease. This would be inadequate at this timepoint and might indicate treatment failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERPR titre 1:24\u003C/strong\u003E at 1 month is too early to assess treatment response, as serological changes take months to manifest. Additionally, this represents less than a single dilution decrease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERPR titre 1:12\u003C/strong\u003E at 12 months represents less than a fourfold decrease, which would be inadequate at this timepoint and suggest treatment failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome patients with late syphilis may maintain persistent low-positive titres despite adequate treatment, known as a serofast state. If RPR titres have decreased fourfold by 6 months and are less than 1:16, no further testing is typically required. However, in late syphilis, monitoring may continue for up to 24 months to ensure adequate response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["RPR titres should decrease at least fourfold within 6-12 months after treatment of syphilis to indicate adequate response, but may take up to 24 months in late syphilis.","Patients with late syphilis may maintain low-positive RPR titres despite adequate treatment (serofast state)."],"references":["Clement ME, Okeke NL, Hicks CB. Treatment of syphilis: a systematic review. JAMA [Internet]. 2014;312(18):1905\u201317. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25387188","Syphilis - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2021. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T00:16:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-26T00:19:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65267"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"202